Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and attach handlers to all six events:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Created     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Created");
        window.Activated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Deactivated");
        window.Stopped     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Stopped");
        window.Resumed     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Resumed");
        window.Destroying  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("[Lifecycle] Destroying");

        return window;
    }
}
```

**Typical sequences you'll see:**

| Scenario | Events |
|---|---|
| App launch | Created ŌåÆ Activated |
| User switches away | Deactivated ŌåÆ Stopped |
| User returns | Resumed ŌåÆ Activated |
| App closed | Stopped ŌåÆ Destroying |

**Key gotchas:**

1. `Resumed` does **not** fire on first launch ŌĆö only after a `Stopped`.
2. On Android, the back button can jump straight to `Destroying` without `Stopped`.
3. `Deactivated` fires for dialogs/notification shade ŌĆö it doesn't always mean backgrounding.

If you also need platform-native callbacks, add `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs` with `#if` directives for Android/iOS/Windows.
